Here's what needs to change for each item in .NET 10:

---

**1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder`**
`WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` / `IWebHostBuilder` are **obsoleted**. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .UseStartup<Startup>()
    .Build();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// move Startup.ConfigureServices → here
var app = builder.Build();
// move Startup.Configure → here
app.Run();
```

---

**2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed**
The per-endpoint `WithOpenApi()` extension is **removed**. Use the document-level approach instead:
```csharp
// Before
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...).WithOpenApi();

// After — register once at the service/app level
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();
// ...
app.MapOpenApi();          // serves the OpenAPI doc at /openapi/v1.json
```
Endpoint metadata (descriptions, tags, etc.) is now applied via attributes or `TypedResults` rather than the `WithOpenApi()` callback overload.

---

**3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` removed**
This MSBuild property and the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers` analyzers are **removed**. Delete the property from your `.csproj`. The built-in `AddOpenApi()` pipeline and the ASP0xxx Roslyn analyzers that ship in the framework handle validation now.

---

**4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag code-gen)**
This package is **deprecated** in .NET 10. Microsoft now ships built-in OpenAPI client generation via `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` replacement tooling based on **Kiota**. If you still need NSwag, pin the package version explicitly — but the recommended migration path is:
```xml
<!-- remove old NSwag/ApiDescription.Client references -->
<!-- use dotnet openapi or Kiota-based generation instead -->
```

---

**5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton**
.NET 10 enforces **DI scope validation by default** (even in Production). Registering `IActionContextAccessor` as a singleton that accesses scoped `ActionContext` data will now throw at startup. Register it as **scoped**:
```csharp
// Before
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor(); // if needed
builder.Services.AddScoped<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();
```

---

**6. `IPNetwork` namespace change**
`Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` is **obsoleted** in favor of the BCL type `System.Net.IPNetwork` (introduced in .NET 8). Update usages:
```csharp
// Before
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After
using System.Net;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
// same constructor-style, different type — the property now accepts System.Net.IPNetwork
```

---

**7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed**
Razor runtime compilation is **removed entirely** in .NET 10. Use **.NET Hot Reload** (`dotnet watch`) instead for dev-time Razor editing:
```bash
dotnet watch run
```
Remove the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` NuGet reference and the `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` call.

---

**8. Cookie auth 401 → redirect behavior**
.NET 10 changes the default `CookieAuthenticationEvents` behavior: requests with `Accept: application/json` (or that lack `text/html`) now receive a **proper 401/403 status** instead of a 302 redirect to the login page. If you had a manual workaround (custom `OnRedirectToLogin`), you can likely **remove it** — the framework handles this automatically now. Verify your API clients still work without the custom event handler.

---

### Quick checklist

| Area | Action |
|---|---|
| Hosting | `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder` |
| OpenAPI | Remove `.WithOpenApi()`; use `AddOpenApi()` + `MapOpenApi()` |
| Analyzers | Delete `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` from csproj |
| Code-gen | Migrate from NSwag/ApiDescription.Client to Kiota |
| DI | `IActionContextAccessor` → scoped registration |
| Networking | `IPNetwork` → `System.Net.IPNetwork` |
| Razor | Remove runtime compilation; use `dotnet watch` |
| Auth | Remove custom 401-redirect workarounds |
